\begin{abstract}
The rapid advancement of Generative AI (GenAI) technologies has opened unprecedented possibilities for independent filmmakers, enabling the creation of cinematic content at a fraction of traditional production costs. However, producing long-form (30+ minutes) narrative films with realistic visual styles using AI tools remains one of the most technically demanding challenges in the field. This paper surveys four principal unsolved problems --- Character Identity Drift (CID), Narrative Temporal Incoherence (NTI), Stochastic Visual Inconsistency (SVI), and Audio Coherence Degradation (ACD) --- and proposes the Agentic Spatial Production Framework (ASPF). ASPF is a conceptual protocol and architectural blueprint integrating 3D spatial pre-construction via Gaussian Splatting, closed-loop multi-agent continuity control, diffusion-based video generation, LoRA-based identity anchoring, and LLM-driven narrative planning. We further introduce the Composite CID-Metric (cCID) and the Audio and Prosodic Drift Index (APDI) as quantitative gating mechanisms. Finally, we provide an analytical cost-benefit projection suggesting a potential order-of-magnitude reduction in production costs. This paper is framed as a framework proposal and protocol definition, explicitly delineating design targets from empirically grounded claims.
\end{abstract}

\textbf{Keywords:} Generative AI, AI Filmmaking, Character Consistency, Long-Form Video Generation, Narrative Coherence, Diffusion Models, LoRA, Gaussian Splatting, Multi-Agent Systems, Audio Coherence

