\section{Introduction}
Generative AI has fundamentally altered the landscape of creative media production. Tools capable of converting text prompts into photorealistic video sequences, synthesizing human voices, and composing adaptive film scores have emerged within fewer than three years. This technological convergence has given rise to a new class of creator: the solo AI filmmaker.

Yet the production of long-form narrative films --- stories exceeding 30 minutes with internally consistent visual worlds --- remains significantly beyond the reliable capability of any existing AI system. The challenge is architectural: current AI generation models are optimized for short, isolated outputs and lack persistent state, identity memory, spatial awareness, and narrative intelligence across extended sequences.

This paper identifies four core unsolved problems, categorizes existing solution strategies, proposes the closed-loop Agentic Spatial Production Framework (ASPF), introduces quantitative identity and audio drift metrics, and provides an analytical cost-benefit projection for independent filmmakers working with current (2025--2026) tooling.

\subsection{Primary Contribution}
The primary contribution of this work is the proposal of the ASPF, a comprehensive architectural blueprint for long-form AI filmmaking. Secondary contributions include the introduction of the Composite CID-Metric (cCID) and the Audio and Prosodic Drift Index (APDI) as quantitative gating mechanisms necessary to automate continuity validation within the proposed agentic loop.

\subsection{Scope and Validation Boundaries}
\textit{This section consolidates the methodological boundaries of this paper.} This work combines a narrative survey of the 2023--2026 literature with a framework proposal and analytical economic projection. It is not a systematic empirical evaluation. Throughout this paper, empirically grounded claims are explicitly cited. All proposed metric thresholds (e.g., cCID, APDI), weighting parameters, and economic projections (e.g., acceptance rates, labor hours) are defined strictly as \textbf{design targets and provisional baselines}. They are provided to establish falsifiable hypotheses for future instrumented case studies and must not be conflated with measured outcomes of completed productions. For brevity, subsequent mentions of these metrics will refer back to this section rather than repeating disclaimers.

