\section{Core Unsolved Problems}

\subsection{Problem I: Character Identity Drift (CID)}
\subsubsection{Definition}
Character Identity Drift is the progressive divergence of a generated character's visual attributes across independently generated video clips.

\subsubsection{Root Causes}
\begin{enumerate}[leftmargin=*]
    \item Stochastic sampling in diffusion models introduces per-generation variance.
    \item Prompt embeddings are lossy encodings; fine visual identity details are not preserved in text space.
    \item Training datasets lack sufficient examples of identical identity across diverse poses.
    \item Multi-character scenes cause identity confusion when embeddings share feature space.
    \item \textbf{Dataset Bias and Cultural Representation Gap:} Foundational models are disproportionately trained on Western cinematic traditions and aesthetic norms. This creates systematic biases in facial structure representation, leading to higher baseline drift and quality degradation when generating non-Western characters without targeted mitigation.
\end{enumerate}

\subsubsection{Quantitative Measurement: The CID-Metric and cCID}
To enable systematic evaluation, we propose the CID-Metric, defined in terms of cosine distance over L2-normalized embeddings:
\begin{equation}
\text{CID}_{\text{mean}} = \frac{1}{N} \sum_{i=1}^{N} \left( 1 - \cos( F(I_{\text{ref}}), F(I_i) ) \right)
\end{equation}
where $F$ is a fixed face-recognition network (e.g., ArcFace). 

\textbf{The Composite CID-Metric (cCID):} To address the facial-only scope limitation, we propose cCID, which combines facial identity with bodily/costume consistency:
\begin{equation}
\text{cCID} = (w_1 \times \text{CID}_{\text{face}}) + (w_2 \times \text{CID}_{\text{body}})
\end{equation}
where $\text{CID}_{\text{body}}$ is derived from a DINOv2 embedding of the character's full bounding box. We suggest provisional weights of \textbf{$w_1 = 0.7$} and \textbf{$w_2 = 0.3$}. This weighting is heuristically initialized based on perceptual-psychology literature indicating that human viewers exhibit substantially higher sensitivity to facial identity drift than to minor clothing or proportional variation (O'Toole et al., 2005). As defined in Section 1.2, these weights are tunable hyperparameters pending human-evaluation.

\subsection{Problem II: Narrative Temporal Incoherence (NTI)}
NTI describes the failure of generated content to maintain consistent story logic and causal coherence. The primary solution is a \textbf{Structured Scene Bible} with a machine-readable world-state (e.g., JSON format), enabling a RAG-based Continuity Agent to perform precise vector-similarity searches against generated shot metadata.

\subsection{Problem III: Stochastic Visual Inconsistency (SVI)}
SVI describes arbitrary variation in lighting, color grade, and environmental details. The primary solution is \textbf{3D Spatial Pre-Construction} using Gaussian Splatting or NeRF to provide geometric and photometric anchoring.

\subsection{Problem IV: Audio Coherence Degradation (ACD)}
ACD encompasses voice ID drift, emotional register inconsistency, and lip-sync degradation. Solutions include Professional Voice Cloning with locked parameters, native audio-visual generation (e.g., Veo 3.1), and the proposed concept of a \textbf{Voice-LoRA} for tonal stability.

\subsubsection{Quantitative Measurement: The Audio and Prosodic Drift Index (APDI)}
To enable automated quality gates for the ACD axis, we propose the APDI:
\begin{equation}
\text{APDI} = \alpha \cdot D_{\text{timbre}} + \beta \cdot D_{\text{formant}} + \gamma \cdot D_{\text{prosody}}
\end{equation}
As an initial working split, we suggest $\alpha = 0.5, \beta = 0.2, \gamma = 0.3$. As stated in Section 1.2, this split is a starting point pending empirical tuning.

