\section{The Agentic Spatial Production Framework (ASPF)}
The ASPF introduces two architectural innovations: (1) 3D spatial pre-construction, and (2) a closed-loop Continuity Agent system.

\subsection{Phase 4: Spatially-Anchored Image Foundation}
Because no major video generation platform currently accepts 3D scene representations as native conditioning inputs, spatial anchoring in the ASPF is achieved indirectly: fixed-viewpoint renders are extracted from the Gaussian Splatting/NeRF environment and serve as reference images via IP-Adapter.

\textbf{Limitation of 2D Projection:} It is critical to acknowledge that converting a 3D volumetric representation into a 2D reference image for an IP-Adapter inherently discards depth and volumetric data. This indirect conditioning acts as a ``soft constraint'' rather than a hard geometric guarantee. The generation model may still deviate from the rendered reference, re-introducing a degree of Stochastic Visual Inconsistency (SVI). This bottleneck is precisely why environmental checks must remain an active part of the Continuity Agent's validation loop (Phase 5), rather than assuming the problem is solved by construction.

