\section{Cultural and Aesthetic Dimension: Validation Protocol}
To transition the cultural analysis (root causes detailed in Sec 3.1.2) from theoretical commentary toward empirical contribution, we propose the following validation protocol as priority future work: a comparative study measuring cCID scores across $N = 500$ generations of Persian/Middle Eastern faces versus European faces on two leading platforms, using the ArcFace/DINOv2 pipeline defined in Section 3.1.3. We emphasize that no such study has yet been conducted, and the existence and magnitude of this ``cultural penalty'' remain an open empirical question.

% ====================================================================
\section{Remaining Open Problems \& Falsifiable Hypotheses}
\begin{itemize}[leftmargin=*]
    \item \textbf{H1 (Cultural penalty):} Base generation pipelines exhibit significantly higher cCID drift for non-Western character generations than for Western character generations under matched prompts.
    \item \textbf{H2 (Continuity Agent labor reduction):} Integration of the closed-loop Continuity Agent reduces manual human review load by at least 50\% relative to a linear, post-hoc review pipeline.
    \item \textbf{H3 (Culturally-specific LoRA mitigation):} Culturally-specific Character LoRA fine-tuning reduces cCID variance for non-Western character generations by at least 40\% relative to base-model generations.
\end{itemize}

