\section{Reference Implementation of the Validation Pipeline}
To support the falsifiable hypotheses and validation protocols proposed throughout this paper, a reference software pipeline has been implemented and is made publicly available at: \url{https://github.com/YOUR_USERNAME/ASPF-Validation-Pipeline}

The pipeline computes the cCID metric (ArcFace face embeddings combined with a DINOv2-based body/costume embedding). Below is the core implementation logic for the cCID calculation, demonstrating the zero-shot deployability of the linear weighted-sum formulation:

\begin{lstlisting}[caption={Core Python Implementation of the cCID Calculator}, label={lst:ccid}]
# See src/ccid_calculator.py for the full, production-ready implementation.
# This snippet demonstrates the core weighted-sum logic.

def calculate_ccid(cid_face: float, cid_body: float, w1: float = 0.7, w2: float = 0.3) -> float:
    total_weight = w1 + w2
    w1_norm = w1 / total_weight
    w2_norm = w2 / total_weight
    ccid_score = (w1_norm * cid_face) + (w2_norm * cid_body)
    return round(ccid_score, 4)
\end{lstlisting}

\textit{Scope Limitations:} As noted in Section 1.2, this code computes drift over static images. Integration with video platform APIs and large-scale demographic datasets (e.g., FairFace for Hypothesis H1) is left as an implementation detail for future instrumented case studies.

